rComments: I would not recommend her at all as Evidence Law is one of the most important courses in law school and the professor should have the necessary skills to teach this class. I switched to Prof. Boivin who teaches the same class in French. Prof. Boivin was delving into case laws and giving concrete examples about the legal principles for clarification

Professor MacDonnell is a great professor. There were two papers for her fall term class, that was it. No exam. She was a fair marker and left a good amount of feedback. The lectures were taught both by youtube videos and on Zoom classes. I would highly recommend Professor MacDonnell.

Professor MacDonnell is very kind and encourages class discussions. Her grading is fair, you just need to put in the effort. However, you won't learn much criminal law. She uses the course to push her personal political views on the class. I worked with a criminal defence lawyer the summer after 1L and had to learn everything from scratch.
The comment below mine is MacDonnel herself conducting damage control. She was not a good professor, don't let the minority of comments fool you.

we have been "blindsided" in all our exams- this tactic is not new to learning. Its an open book exam-obviously our prof is going to test something hard. In regards to "prescribe to a philosophy" .. professors are not robots, they come from a diverse backgrounds and bring there experience to the classroom. PVM is engaging, smart & thoughtful.

Although seemingly approachable, her feedback and expectations are unclear. Comments are not provided on assignments. Classes can often be disorganized. Unfettered class discussion detracts from discussing actual topics from readings and varying viewpoints are unwelcome. Final exam not as described, not reflective of class, fact pattern confusing.
Be to get blind sided on your exam; you will get tested on unsubstantial material.

HER EXPECTATIONS ARE UNCLEAR. Impossible to do well if I have no idea what she's looking for. She give you NO guidelines for assignments, but gives you a bad grade if you didn't speak about a certain principle that you didn't learn in class yet. When you ask why you got your mark (bc there's NO comments on your paper) she says bc theres a curve....

I really enjoyed learning from Professor MacDonnell. She was principled in her views and inspirational to learn from. She is a tough marker but fair; she makes you work for it. Her views are progressive but she is open to hearing and engaging with students from varying viewpoints. Get to know her expectations, fulfill them, and you'll be fine.

Arbitrary grading and unclear what she expects in assignments/exams. Poor instructor with little attention given to substantial material. More interested in hearing her own opinions echoed in class discussion.

You do NOT learn much about the criminal law in this class. It's more of a "everyone talk about your feelings on this" type thing. I'm so disappointed. Literally learned nothing from in class. Don't even bother showing up, just read the book and teach yourself everything. She's a really tough marker, even though she gives you guidelines or criteria

I learned nothing in this class. MacDonnel is the archetypical nice professor that slaps you in the face come exam time. Don't bother going to class, she doesn't teach you anything anyway. Just get a summary from last year and learn the content a few days before the exam and you'll do fine.

Doesn't separate her opinions from class material or have a disclaimer about her ideas. This bothered me because if you don't have a strong leftist or feminist views, it can be discouraging to speak up - not well-balanced in diff perspectives. Also, she revised her syllabus 8+ times b/c we always go on tangents. Hard grader on papers, cite well!

She teaches from a case her husband did and has no experience in actual advocacy or lawyering. Just buy the "Law of Evidence" text since she teaches from that text but has different readings on the syllabus. I would not recommend you take her class if you want to learn anything though.
Best professor ever (real or fictional)
Professor MacDonnell was excellent at generating class discussion and she was clearly knowledgeable about the Charter of Rights and Freedoms. Her lectures were excellent.

Here's a nice lady who tries hard. Too hard. Her exaggerated responses to everything said in the class include erudite gems such as "Oh, that's really important" or "That's very interesting", or "I'm glad you said that". No class is that entertaining and, for that matter, neither is she. She has knowledge but lacks depth and experience and it shows

Professor MacDonnell is clear, organized, and encourages class participation. Our evaluation was a moot, involving a factum & oral component. The factum assignment was challenging and probably could have used clarificationfurther instructions, but overall, it was a valuable learning experience. I'd recommend her class.

The professor spoon feeds the class on a narrow set of issues.  Almost all the time is spent on hearsay and character evidence.  She does not want original research; in your factum use primarily and almost exclusively what she presents on powerpoint.  Remember to write factum re trial level not appellate.

This professor was a complete mess and so was her class.  Her assignments were marked reasonably, but I learned virtually NOTHING about the law of evidence, aside from 3 extremely narrow criminal issues on which she based the course.  She does not know how to organize a course, nor how to teach a class.  Avoid at all costs!

This Professor is overall acceptable. She knows the material fairly well and communicates it effectively.    I found her feedback completely useless. On papers and assignments, it was clear she did not consider student enhancement to be the purpose of feedback.

A very nice woman, obviously cares about her students. However, make no mistake here. This is an extremely hard course, you will need to devote more time to it than the average course - so if your course load is heavy forget about it. The exam is horrible.
